hasizing her resulting mental illness; Fadi, who highlighted the homophobic motivations that provoked his arrest and torture in Jordan, all the while sidelining connected issues of class and racism; and Marwa, who showcased her private hardships as a lesbian in a Shiite family in Lebanon and downplayed her environmental activism. The Right Kind of Suffering is a compelling portrait of Arab asylum seekers whose success stories stand in contrast with those whom the system failed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aAsylum, Right ofzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aGay political refugeesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aGay political refugeeszArab countriesvCase studies. 0aPolitical refugeesxLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aPolitical refugeeszArab countriesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079782440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/32638140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781477326398423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781477326398/original  a978-3-11-079782-4  University of Texas Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK